1
00:00:18,209 --> 00:00:28,780
TO SOME HE was a military genius, strategic mastermind and visionary leader who bequeathed to France a centralised modern administration and sense of gloire.

2
00:00:29,610 --> 00:00:35,860
To others he was a tyrant and a butcher who squandered French supremacy in Europe on the battlefield of Waterloo.

3
00:00:36,219 --> 00:00:47,220
Napoleon Bonaparte, who died in captivity on the British island of Saint Helena at the age of 51, has long inspired both admiration and distaste, even in France.

4
00:00:47,660 --> 00:00:54,710
Now, ahead of the bicentenary of his death on May 5th 1821, those rival passions have been revived.

5
00:00:55,379 --> 00:01:03,920
Alexis Corbière, a deputy from Unsubmissive France, a left-wing party, declared:“It is not for the republic to celebrate its gravedigger.”

6
00:01:05,059 --> 00:01:12,660
On the right Jean-Louis Debré, formerly head of the constitutional council, said that“overdoing it”would be“a provocation”.

7
00:01:13,320 --> 00:01:22,669
The Black Lives Matter movement has emboldened those who reject any celebration of a leader who reintroduced slavery to the French West Indies in 1802.

8
00:01:24,050 --> 00:01:35,240
Nicolas Mayer-Rossignol, the Socialist mayor of Rouen, says he wants to replace the imposing bronze statue of the emperor on horseback that stands outside his Normandy town hall.

9
00:01:36,030 --> 00:01:46,080
Yet the French also acknowledge that they owe much of their modern state, and its institutions, not to mention their country’s aspiration to grandeur, to the“little Corsican”.

10
00:01:46,609 --> 00:01:58,550
As first consul, Napoleon created the French legal code, the Bank of France, the administrative system of préfets, high-school lycées, the légion d’honneur and much more.

11
00:01:59,080 --> 00:02:05,930
In a poll in 2016 he was listed as the second-most-important Frenchman in history, after Charles de Gaulle.

12
00:02:06,359 --> 00:02:15,270
His red quartzite tomb in Les Invalides, lying in splendid isolation in a crypt beneath the dome, receives over a million visitors a year.

13
00:02:15,929 --> 00:02:24,209
This spring scores of new books are promised, says the Fondation Napoléon, as well as conferences and a big exhibition in Paris.

14
00:02:24,549 --> 00:02:37,069
“We have every reason to be proud of him,”said Patrice Gueniffey, a historian, who considers him a historical figure on a par with Alexander the Great or Julius Caesar (both of whom also killed a lot of people).

15
00:02:37,799 --> 00:02:41,300
President Emmanuel Macron has not yet shown his hand.

16
00:02:41,670 --> 00:02:53,350
In 2005 Jacques Chirac, a Gaullist predecessor at the Elysée Palace, refused—amid protests at the time—to commemorate the bicentenary of Napoleon’s victory at Austerlitz.

17
00:02:53,880 --> 00:03:00,099
Talk shows have been debating what to do this year, and whether his legacy is damaging or beneficial for France.

18
00:03:00,449 --> 00:03:08,580
An adept of“en même temps”, or the improbable art of reconciling opposing views, Mr Macron has his work cut out.

